# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 3f — Topology+phase refined-scan surfaced (fourth scan round)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Fourth scan in the autoresearch loop. The refined scoring lives in
# `scripts/scan_dyad_candidates.py` and layers two new signals on top
# of PR #1996's Hz+cross-ref+lineage+same-form score:
#
#   score = 1.0*cross_ref + 0.6*hz_proximity + 0.3*lineage_match
#         + 0.4*same_form + 0.4*topology_complementarity
#         + 0.4*phase_complementarity
#
# topology_complementarity: named complementary topology pairs (1.5);
#   same topology (0.5); else 0. The complementary set is authored
#   from what actually appears in the body's signatures —
#   radial↔web-each-to-each (gather↔distribute), hub-spoke↔web-each-
#   to-each (broadcast↔mesh), radial↔receptive-resonance (source↔sink),
#   nested-each-contains-whole↔web-each-to-each (holography↔mesh),
#   linear↔cyclic-closed (arc↔loop), self-rooted↔receptive-resonance
#   (sovereignty↔receipt).
#
# phase_complementarity: named complementary phases (1.5); same phase
#   (0.5); else 0. yang↔yin is canonical; the body's signatures also
#   carry oscillating↔yin (the event oscillates on the still ground),
#   oscillating↔neutral, and yang↔neutral.
#
# The hypothesis: dyad-pairs typically carry complementary topology
# or complementary phase, not just shared shape. Layering both
# signals should sharpen discernment of complementarity vs equivalence.
#
# Result of top-10 assessment: 4 confirmed / 10 = 40%. Same ratio as
# PR #1996. The saturation finding HOLDS at this deeper layer — the
# geometry vocabulary, even with topology+phase complementarity rules,
# saturates because many cells genuinely ARE yang/yin pairs in shape
# without being teaching-complementary. The next refinement direction
# is prose-structural (WORD-domain lemma chains, shared semantic
# field) rather than further geometry-tuple weighting.
#
# Four confirmed pairs from the top-10 scan-discovered + sweep below.

